4 /** \file
5  *
6  * Generator is a class used to encapsulate the building of Funcs in user
7  * pipelines. A Generator is agnostic to JIT vs AOT compilation; it can be used for
8  * either purpose, but is especially convenient to use for AOT compilation.
9  *
10  * A Generator explicitly declares the Inputs and Outputs associated for a given
11  * pipeline, and (optionally) separates the code for constructing the outputs from the code from
12  * scheduling them. For instance:
13  *
14  * \code
15  * class Blur : public Generator<Blur> {
16  * public:
17  * Input<Func> input{"input", UInt(16), 2};
18  * Output<Func> output{"output", UInt(16), 2};
19  * void generate() {
20  * blur_x(x, y) = (input(x, y) + input(x+1, y) + input(x+2, y))/3;
21  * blur_y(x, y) = (blur_x(x, y) + blur_x(x, y+1) + blur_x(x, y+2))/3;
22  * output(x, y) = blur(x, y);
23  * }
24  * void schedule() {
25  * blur_y.split(y, y, yi, 8).parallel(y).vectorize(x, 8);
26  * blur_x.store_at(blur_y, y).compute_at(blur_y, yi).vectorize(x, 8);
27  * }
28  * private:
29  * Var x, y, xi, yi;
30  * Func blur_x, blur_y;
31  * };
32  * \endcode
33  *
34  * Halide can compile a Generator into the correct pipeline by introspecting these
35  * values and constructing an appropriate signature based on them.
36  *
37  * A Generator provides implementations of two methods:
38  *
39  * - generate(), which must fill in all Output Func(s); it may optionally also do scheduling
40  * if no schedule() method is present.
41  * - schedule(), which (if present) should contain all scheduling code.
42  *
43  * Inputs can be any C++ scalar type:
44  *
45  * \code
46  * Input<float> radius{"radius"};
47  * Input<int32_t> increment{"increment"};
48  * \endcode
49  *
50  * An Input<Func> is (essentially) like an ImageParam, except that it may (or may
51  * not) not be backed by an actual buffer, and thus has no defined extents.
52  *
53  * \code
54  * Input<Func> input{"input", Float(32), 2};
55  * \endcode
56  *
57  * You can optionally make the type and/or dimensions of Input<Func> unspecified,
58  * in which case the value is simply inferred from the actual Funcs passed to them.
59  * Of course, if you specify an explicit Type or Dimension, we still require the
60  * input Func to match, or a compilation error results.
61  *
62  * \code
63  * Input<Func> input{ "input", 3 }; // require 3-dimensional Func,
64  * // but leave Type unspecified
65  * \endcode
66  *
67  * A Generator must explicitly list the output(s) it produces:
68  *
69  * \code
70  * Output<Func> output{"output", Float(32), 2};
71  * \endcode
72  *
73  * You can specify an output that returns a Tuple by specifying a list of Types:
74  *
75  * \code
76  * class Tupler : Generator<Tupler> {
77  * Input<Func> input{"input", Int(32), 2};
78  * Output<Func> output{"output", {Float(32), UInt(8)}, 2};
79  * void generate() {
80  * Var x, y;
81  * Expr a = cast<float>(input(x, y));
82  * Expr b = cast<uint8_t>(input(x, y));
83  * output(x, y) = Tuple(a, b);
84  * }
85  * };
86  * \endcode
87  *
88  * You can also specify Output<X> for any scalar type (except for Handle types);
89  * this is merely syntactic sugar on top of a zero-dimensional Func, but can be
90  * quite handy, especially when used with multiple outputs:
91  *
92  * \code
93  * Output<float> sum{"sum"}; // equivalent to Output<Func> {"sum", Float(32), 0}
94  * \endcode
95  *
96  * As with Input<Func>, you can optionally make the type and/or dimensions of an
97  * Output<Func> unspecified; any unspecified types must be resolved via an
98  * implicit GeneratorParam in order to use top-level compilation.
99  *
100  * You can also declare an *array* of Input or Output, by using an array type
101  * as the type parameter:
102  *
103  * \code
104  * // Takes exactly 3 images and outputs exactly 3 sums.
105  * class SumRowsAndColumns : Generator<SumRowsAndColumns> {
106  * Input<Func[3]> inputs{"inputs", Float(32), 2};
107  * Input<int32_t[2]> extents{"extents"};
108  * Output<Func[3]> sums{"sums", Float(32), 1};
109  * void generate() {
110  * assert(inputs.size() == sums.size());
111  * // assume all inputs are same extent
112  * Expr width = extent[0];
113  * Expr height = extent[1];
114  * for (size_t i = 0; i < inputs.size(); ++i) {
115  * RDom r(0, width, 0, height);
116  * sums[i]() = 0.f;
117  * sums[i]() += inputs[i](r.x, r.y);
118  * }
119  * }
120  * };
121  * \endcode
122  *
123  * You can also leave array size unspecified, with some caveats:
124  * - For ahead-of-time compilation, Inputs must have a concrete size specified
125  * via a GeneratorParam at build time (e.g., pyramid.size=3)
126  * - For JIT compilation via a Stub, Inputs array sizes will be inferred
127  * from the vector passed.
128  * - For ahead-of-time compilation, Outputs may specify a concrete size
129  * via a GeneratorParam at build time (e.g., pyramid.size=3), or the
130  * size can be specified via a resize() method.
131  *
132  * \code
133  * class Pyramid : public Generator<Pyramid> {
134  * public:
135  * GeneratorParam<int32_t> levels{"levels", 10};
136  * Input<Func> input{ "input", Float(32), 2 };
137  * Output<Func[]> pyramid{ "pyramid", Float(32), 2 };
138  * void generate() {
139  * pyramid.resize(levels);
140  * pyramid[0](x, y) = input(x, y);
141  * for (int i = 1; i < pyramid.size(); i++) {
142  * pyramid[i](x, y) = (pyramid[i-1](2*x, 2*y) +
143  * pyramid[i-1](2*x+1, 2*y) +
144  * pyramid[i-1](2*x, 2*y+1) +
145  * pyramid[i-1](2*x+1, 2*y+1))/4;
146  * }
147  * }
148  * };
149  * \endcode
150  *
151  * A Generator can also be customized via compile-time parameters (GeneratorParams),
152  * which affect code generation.
153  *
154  * GeneratorParams, Inputs, and Outputs are (by convention) always
155  * public and always declared at the top of the Generator class, in the order
156  *
157  * \code
158  * GeneratorParam(s)
159  * Input<Func>(s)
160  * Input<non-Func>(s)
161  * Output<Func>(s)
162  * \endcode
163  *
164  * Note that the Inputs and Outputs will appear in the C function call in the order
165  * they are declared. All Input<Func> and Output<Func> are represented as halide_buffer_t;
166  * all other Input<> are the appropriate C++ scalar type. (GeneratorParams are
167  * always referenced by name, not position, so their order is irrelevant.)
168  *
169  * All Inputs and Outputs must have explicit names, and all such names must match
170  * the regex [A-Za-z][A-Za-z_0-9]* (i.e., essentially a C/C++ variable name, with
171  * some extra restrictions on underscore use). By convention, the name should match
172  * the member-variable name.
173  *
174  * You can dynamically add Inputs and Outputs to your Generator via adding a
175  * configure() method; if present, it will be called before generate(). It can
176  * examine GeneratorParams but it may not examine predeclared Inputs or Outputs;
177  * the only thing it should do is call add_input<>() and/or add_output<>().
178  * Added inputs will be appended (in order) after predeclared Inputs but before
179  * any Outputs; added outputs will be appended after predeclared Outputs.
180  *
181  * Note that the pointers returned by add_input() and add_output() are owned
182  * by the Generator and will remain valid for the Generator's lifetime; user code
183  * should not attempt to delete or free them.
184  *
185  * \code
186  * class MultiSum : public Generator<MultiSum> {
187  * public:
188  * GeneratorParam<int32_t> input_count{"input_count", 10};
189  * Output<Func> output{ "output", Float(32), 2 };
190  *
191  * void configure() {
192  * for (int i = 0; i < input_count; ++i) {
193  * extra_inputs.push_back(
194  * add_input<Func>("input_" + std::to_string(i), Float(32), 2);
195  * }
196  * }
197  *
198  * void generate() {
199  * Expr sum = 0.f;
200  * for (int i = 0; i < input_count; ++i) {
201  * sum += (*extra_inputs)[i](x, y);
202  * }
203  * output(x, y) = sum;
204  * }
205  * private:
206  * std::vector<Input<Func>* extra_inputs;
207  * };
208  * \endcode
209  *
210  * All Generators have three GeneratorParams that are implicitly provided
211  * by the base class:
212  *
213  * GeneratorParam<Target> target{"target", Target()};
214  * GeneratorParam<bool> auto_schedule{"auto_schedule", false};
215  * GeneratorParam<MachineParams> machine_params{"machine_params", MachineParams::generic()};
216  *
217  * - 'target' is the Halide::Target for which the Generator is producing code.
218  * It is read-only during the Generator's lifetime, and must not be modified;
219  * its value should always be filled in by the calling code: either the Halide
220  * build system (for ahead-of-time compilation), or ordinary C++ code
221  * (for JIT compilation).
222  * - 'auto_schedule' indicates whether the auto-scheduler should be run for this
223  * Generator:
224  * - if 'false', the Generator should schedule its Funcs as it sees fit.
225  * - if 'true', the Generator should only provide estimate()s for its Funcs,
226  * and not call any other scheduling methods.
227  * - 'machine_params' is only used if auto_schedule is true; it is ignored
228  * if auto_schedule is false. It provides details about the machine architecture
229  * being targeted which may be used to enhance the automatically-generated
230  * schedule.
231  *
232  * Generators are added to a global registry to simplify AOT build mechanics; this
233  * is done by simply using the HALIDE_REGISTER_GENERATOR macro at global scope:
234  *
235  * \code
236  * HALIDE_REGISTER_GENERATOR(ExampleGen, jit_example)
237  * \endcode
238  *
239  * The registered name of the Generator is provided must match the same rules as
240  * Input names, above.
241  *
242  * Note that the class name of the generated Stub class will match the registered
243  * name by default; if you want to vary it (typically, to include namespaces),
244  * you can add it as an optional third argument:
245  *
246  * \code
247  * HALIDE_REGISTER_GENERATOR(ExampleGen, jit_example, SomeNamespace::JitExampleStub)
248  * \endcode
249  *
250  * Note that a Generator is always executed with a specific Target assigned to it,
251  * that you can access via the get_target() method. (You should *not* use the
252  * global get_target_from_environment(), etc. methods provided in Target.h)
253  *
254  * (Note that there are older variations of Generator that differ from what's
255  * documented above; these are still supported but not described here. See
256  * https://github.com/halide/Halide/wiki/Old-Generator-Documentation for
257  * more information.)
258  */

288 /**
289  * ValueTracker is an internal utility class that attempts to track and flag certain
290  * obvious Stub-related errors at Halide compile time: it tracks the constraints set
291  * on any Parameter-based argument (i.e., Input<Buffer> and Output<Buffer>) to
292  * ensure that incompatible values aren't set.
293  *
294  * e.g.: if a Generator A requires stride[0] == 1,
295  * and Generator B uses Generator A via stub, but requires stride[0] == 4,
296  * we should be able to detect this at Halide compilation time, and fail immediately,
297  * rather than producing code that fails at runtime and/or runs slowly due to
298  * vectorization being unavailable.
299  *
300  * We do this by tracking the active values at entrance and exit to all user-provided
301  * Generator methods (build()/generate()/schedule()); if we ever find more than two unique
302  * values active, we know we have a potential conflict. ("two" here because the first
303  * value is the default value for a given constraint.)
304  *
305  * Note that this won't catch all cases:
306  * -- JIT compilation has no way to check for conflicts at the top-level
307  * -- constraints that match the default value (e.g. if dim(0).set_stride(1) is the
308  * first value seen by the tracker) will be ignored, so an explicit requirement set
309  * this way can be missed
310  *
311  * Nevertheless, this is likely to be much better than nothing when composing multiple
312  * layers of Stubs in a single fused result.
313  */
314 class ValueTracker {
315 private:
316  std::map<std::string, std::vector<std::vector<Expr>>> values_history;
317  const size_t max_unique_values;
318 
319 public:
320  explicit ValueTracker(size_t max_unique_values = 2)
321  : max_unique_values(max_unique_values) {
322  }
323  void track_values(const std::string &name, const std::vector<Expr> &values);
324 };

364 // select_type<> is to std::conditional as switch is to if:
365 // it allows a multiway compile-time type definition via the form
366 //
367 // select_type<cond<condition1, type1>,
368 // cond<condition2, type2>,
369 // ....
370 // cond<conditionN, typeN>>::type
371 //
372 // Note that the conditions are evaluated in order; the first evaluating to true
373 // is chosen.
374 //
375 // Note that if no conditions evaluate to true, the resulting type is illegal
376 // and will produce a compilation error. (You can provide a default by simply
377 // using cond<true, SomeType> as the final entry.)
378 template<bool B, typename T>
379 struct cond {
380  static constexpr bool value = B;
381  using type = T;
382 };

568  // If FROM and T are identical, just assign
569  template<typename FROM, typename std::enable_if<
570  std::is_same<FROM, T>::value>::type * = nullptr>
571  HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE void typed_setter_impl(const FROM &value, const char *msg) {
572  check_value_writable();
573  value_ = value;
574  }
575 
576  // If both FROM->T and T->FROM are legal, ensure it's lossless
577  template<typename FROM, typename std::enable_if<
578  !std::is_same<FROM, T>::value &&
579  std::is_convertible<FROM, T>::value &&
580  std::is_convertible<T, FROM>::value>::type * = nullptr>
581  HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE void typed_setter_impl(const FROM &value, const char *msg) {
582  check_value_writable();
583  const T t = Convert<FROM, T>::value(value);
584  const FROM value2 = Convert<T, FROM>::value(t);
585  if (value2 != value) {
586  fail_wrong_type(msg);
587  }
588  value_ = t;
589  }
590 
591  // If FROM->T is legal but T->FROM is not, just assign
592  template<typename FROM, typename std::enable_if<
593  !std::is_same<FROM, T>::value &&
594  std::is_convertible<FROM, T>::value &&
595  !std::is_convertible<T, FROM>::value>::type * = nullptr>
596  HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE void typed_setter_impl(const FROM &value, const char *msg) {
597  check_value_writable();
598  value_ = value;
599  }
600 };

659 class GeneratorParam_LoopLevel : public GeneratorParamImpl<LoopLevel> {
660 public:
661  GeneratorParam_LoopLevel(const std::string &name, const LoopLevel &value)
662  : GeneratorParamImpl<LoopLevel>(name, value) {
663  }
664 
665  using GeneratorParamImpl<LoopLevel>::set;
666 
667  void set(const LoopLevel &value) override {
668  // Don't call check_value_writable(): It's OK to set a LoopLevel after generate().
669  // check_value_writable();
670 
671  // This looks odd, but is deliberate:
672 
673  // First, mutate the existing contents to match the value passed in,
674  // so that any existing usage of the LoopLevel now uses the newer value.
675  // (Strictly speaking, this is really only necessary if this method
676  // is called after generate(): before generate(), there is no usage
677  // to be concerned with.)
678  value_.set(value);
679 
680  // Then, reset the value itself so that it points to the same LoopLevelContents
681  // as the value passed in. (Strictly speaking, this is really only
682  // useful if this method is called before generate(): afterwards, it's
683  // too late to alter the code to refer to a different LoopLevelContents.)
684  value_ = value;
685  }
686 
687  void set_from_string(const std::string &new_value_string) override {
688  if (new_value_string == "root") {
689  this->set(LoopLevel::root());
690  } else if (new_value_string == "inlined") {
691  this->set(LoopLevel::inlined());
692  } else {
693  user_error << "Unable to parse " << this->name() << ": " << new_value_string;
694  }
695  }
696 
697  std::string get_default_value() const override {
698  // This is dodgy but safe in this case: we want to
699  // see what the value of our LoopLevel is *right now*,
700  // so we make a copy and lock the copy so we can inspect it.
701  // (Note that ordinarily this is a bad idea, since LoopLevels
702  // can be mutated later on; however, this method is only
703  // called by the Generator infrastructure, on LoopLevels that
704  // will never be mutated, so this is really just an elaborate way
705  // to avoid runtime assertions.)
706  LoopLevel copy;
707  copy.set(this->value());
708  copy.lock();
709  if (copy.is_inlined()) {
710  return "LoopLevel::inlined()";
711  } else if (copy.is_root()) {
712  return "LoopLevel::root()";
713  } else {
714  internal_error;
715  return "";
716  }
717  }
718 
719  std::string call_to_string(const std::string &v) const override {
720  internal_error;
721  return std::string();
722  }
723 
724  std::string get_c_type() const override {
725  return "LoopLevel";
726  }
727 
728  bool is_looplevel_param() const override {
729  return true;
730  }
731 };

733 template<typename T>
734 class GeneratorParam_Arithmetic : public GeneratorParamImpl<T> {
735 public:
736  GeneratorParam_Arithmetic(const std::string &name,
737  const T &value,
738  const T &min = std::numeric_limits<T>::lowest(),
739  const T &max = std::numeric_limits<T>::max())
740  : GeneratorParamImpl<T>(name, value), min(min), max(max) {
741  // call set() to ensure value is clamped to min/max
742  this->set(value);
743  }
744 
745  void set_impl(const T &new_value) override {
746  user_assert(new_value >= min && new_value <= max) << "Value out of range: " << new_value;
747  GeneratorParamImpl<T>::set_impl(new_value);
748  }
749 
750  void set_from_string(const std::string &new_value_string) override {
751  std::istringstream iss(new_value_string);
752  T t;
753  // All one-byte ints int8 and uint8 should be parsed as integers, not chars --
754  // including 'char' itself. (Note that sizeof(bool) is often-but-not-always-1,
755  // so be sure to exclude that case.)
756  if (sizeof(T) == sizeof(char) && !std::is_same<T, bool>::value) {
757  int i;
758  iss >> i;
759  t = (T)i;
760  } else {
761  iss >> t;
762  }
763  user_assert(!iss.fail() && iss.get() == EOF) << "Unable to parse: " << new_value_string;
764  this->set(t);
765  }
766 
767  std::string get_default_value() const override {
768  std::ostringstream oss;
769  oss << this->value();
770  if (std::is_same<T, float>::value) {
771  // If the constant has no decimal point ("1")
772  // we must append one before appending "f"
773  if (oss.str().find('.') == std::string::npos) {
774  oss << ".";
775  }
776  oss << "f";
777  }
778  return oss.str();
779  }
780 
781  std::string call_to_string(const std::string &v) const override {
782  std::ostringstream oss;
783  oss << "std::to_string(" << v << ")";
784  return oss.str();
785  }
786 
787  std::string get_c_type() const override {
788  std::ostringstream oss;
789  if (std::is_same<T, float>::value) {
790  return "float";
791  } else if (std::is_same<T, double>::value) {
792  return "double";
793  } else if (std::is_integral<T>::value) {
794  if (std::is_unsigned<T>::value) {
795  oss << "u";
796  }
797  oss << "int" << (sizeof(T) * 8) << "_t";
798  return oss.str();
799  } else {
800  user_error << "Unknown arithmetic type\n";
801  return "";
802  }
803  }
804 
805 private:
806  const T min, max;
807 };

843 template<typename T>
844 class GeneratorParam_Enum : public GeneratorParamImpl<T> {
845 public:
846  GeneratorParam_Enum(const std::string &name, const T &value, const std::map<std::string, T> &enum_map)
847  : GeneratorParamImpl<T>(name, value), enum_map(enum_map) {
848  }
849 
850  // define a "set" that takes our specific enum (but don't hide the inherited virtual functions)
851  using GeneratorParamImpl<T>::set;
852 
853  template<typename T2 = T, typename std::enable_if<!std::is_same<T2, Type>::value>::type * = nullptr>
854  void set(const T &e) {
855  this->set_impl(e);
856  }
857 
858  void set_from_string(const std::string &new_value_string) override {
859  auto it = enum_map.find(new_value_string);
860  user_assert(it != enum_map.end()) << "Enumeration value not found: " << new_value_string;
861  this->set_impl(it->second);
862  }
863 
864  std::string call_to_string(const std::string &v) const override {
865  return "Enum_" + this->name() + "_map().at(" + v + ")";
866  }
867 
868  std::string get_c_type() const override {
869  return "Enum_" + this->name();
870  }
871 
872  std::string get_default_value() const override {
873  return "Enum_" + this->name() + "::" + enum_to_string(enum_map, this->value());
874  }
875 
876  std::string get_type_decls() const override {
877  std::ostringstream oss;
878  oss << "enum class Enum_" << this->name() << " {\n";
879  for (auto key_value : enum_map) {
880  oss << " " << key_value.first << ",\n";
881  }
882  oss << "};\n";
883  oss << "\n";
884 
885  // TODO: since we generate the enums, we could probably just use a vector (or array!) rather than a map,
886  // since we can ensure that the enum values are a nice tight range.
887  oss << "inline HALIDE_NO_USER_CODE_INLINE const std::map<Enum_" << this->name() << ", std::string>& Enum_" << this->name() << "_map() {\n";
888  oss << " static const std::map<Enum_" << this->name() << ", std::string> m = {\n";
889  for (auto key_value : enum_map) {
890  oss << " { Enum_" << this->name() << "::" << key_value.first << ", \"" << key_value.first << "\"},\n";
891  }
892  oss << " };\n";
893  oss << " return m;\n";
894  oss << "};\n";
895  return oss.str();
896  }
897 
898 private:
899  const std::map<std::string, T> enum_map;
900 };

963 /** GeneratorParam is a templated class that can be used to modify the behavior
964  * of the Generator at code-generation time. GeneratorParams are commonly
965  * specified in build files (e.g. Makefile) to customize the behavior of
966  * a given Generator, thus they have a very constrained set of types to allow
967  * for efficient specification via command-line flags. A GeneratorParam can be:
968  * - any float or int type.
969  * - bool
970  * - enum
971  * - Halide::Target
972  * - Halide::Type
973  * - std::string
974  * Please don't use std::string unless there's no way to do what you want with some
975  * other type; in particular, don't use this if you can use enum instead.
976  * All GeneratorParams have a default value. Arithmetic types can also
977  * optionally specify min and max. Enum types must specify a string-to-value
978  * map.
979  *
980  * Halide::Type is treated as though it were an enum, with the mappings:
981  *
982  * "int8" Halide::Int(8)
983  * "int16" Halide::Int(16)
984  * "int32" Halide::Int(32)
985  * "uint8" Halide::UInt(8)
986  * "uint16" Halide::UInt(16)
987  * "uint32" Halide::UInt(32)
988  * "float32" Halide::Float(32)
989  * "float64" Halide::Float(64)
990  *
991  * No vector Types are currently supported by this mapping.
992  *
993  */
994 template<typename T>
995 class GeneratorParam : public Internal::GeneratorParamImplBase<T> {
996 public:
997  template<typename T2 = T, typename std::enable_if<!std::is_same<T2, std::string>::value>::type * = nullptr>
998  GeneratorParam(const std::string &name, const T &value)
999  : Internal::GeneratorParamImplBase<T>(name, value) {
1000  }
1001 
1002  GeneratorParam(const std::string &name, const T &value, const T &min, const T &max)
1003  : Internal::GeneratorParamImplBase<T>(name, value, min, max) {
1004  }
1005 
1006  GeneratorParam(const std::string &name, const T &value, const std::map<std::string, T> &enum_map)
1007  : Internal::GeneratorParamImplBase<T>(name, value, enum_map) {
1008  }
1009 
1010  GeneratorParam(const std::string &name, const std::string &value)
1011  : Internal::GeneratorParamImplBase<T>(name, value) {
1012  }
1013 };

1264 /**
1265  * StubInputBuffer is the placeholder that a Stub uses when it requires
1266  * a Buffer for an input (rather than merely a Func or Expr). It is constructed
1267  * to allow only two possible sorts of input:
1268  * -- Assignment of an Input<Buffer<>>, with compatible type and dimensions,
1269  * essentially allowing us to pipe a parameter from an enclosing Generator to an internal Stub.
1270  * -- Assignment of a Buffer<>, with compatible type and dimensions,
1271  * causing the Input<Buffer<>> to become a precompiled buffer in the generated code.
1272  */
1273 template<typename T = void>
1274 class StubInputBuffer {
1275  friend class StubInput;
1276  template<typename T2>
1277  friend class GeneratorInput_Buffer;
1278 
1279  Parameter parameter_;
1280 
1281  HALIDE_NO_USER_CODE_INLINE explicit StubInputBuffer(const Parameter &p)
1282  : parameter_(p) {
1283  // Create an empty 1-element buffer with the right runtime typing and dimensions,
1284  // which we'll use only to pass to can_convert_from() to verify this
1285  // Parameter is compatible with our constraints.
1286  Buffer<> other(p.type(), nullptr, std::vector<int>(p.dimensions(), 1));
1287  internal_assert((Buffer<T>::can_convert_from(other)));
1288  }
1289 
1290  template<typename T2>
1291  HALIDE_NO_USER_CODE_INLINE static Parameter parameter_from_buffer(const Buffer<T2> &b) {
1292  user_assert((Buffer<T>::can_convert_from(b)));
1293  Parameter p(b.type(), true, b.dimensions());
1294  p.set_buffer(b);
1295  return p;
1296  }
1297 
1298 public:
1299  StubInputBuffer() = default;
1300 
1301  // *not* explicit -- this ctor should only be used when you want
1302  // to pass a literal Buffer<> for a Stub Input; this Buffer<> will be
1303  // compiled into the Generator's product, rather than becoming
1304  // a runtime Parameter.
1305  template<typename T2>
1306  StubInputBuffer(const Buffer<T2> &b)
1307  : parameter_(parameter_from_buffer(b)) {
1308  }
1309 };

1415 /** GIOBase is the base class for all GeneratorInput<> and GeneratorOutput<>
1416  * instantiations; it is not part of the public API and should never be
1417  * used directly by user code.
1418  *
1419  * Every GIOBase instance can be either a single value or an array-of-values;
1420  * each of these values can be an Expr or a Func. (Note that for an
1421  * array-of-values, the types/dimensions of all values in the array must match.)
1422  *
1423  * A GIOBase can have multiple Types, in which case it represents a Tuple.
1424  * (Note that Tuples are currently only supported for GeneratorOutput, but
1425  * it is likely that GeneratorInput will be extended to support Tuple as well.)
1426  *
1427  * The array-size, type(s), and dimensions can all be left "unspecified" at
1428  * creation time, in which case they may assume values provided by a Stub.
1429  * (It is important to note that attempting to use a GIOBase with unspecified
1430  * values will assert-fail; you must ensure that all unspecified values are
1431  * filled in prior to use.)
1432  */

1465  // -1 if is_array() == true but unspecified.
1466

1468  const IOKind kind_;
1469  mutable std::vector<Type> types_; // empty if type is unspecified
1470  mutable int dims_; // -1 if dim is unspecified
1471

1624 // When forwarding methods to ImageParam, Func, etc., we must take
1625 // care with the return types: many of the methods return a reference-to-self
1626 // (e.g., ImageParam&); since we create temporaries for most of these forwards,
1627 // returning a ref will crater because it refers to a now-defunct section of the
1628 // stack. Happily, simply removing the reference is solves this, since all of the
1629 // types in question satisfy the property of copies referring to the same underlying
1630 // structure (returning references is just an optimization). Since this is verbose
1631 // and used in several places, we'll use a helper macro:
1632 #define HALIDE_FORWARD_METHOD(Class, Method) \
1633  template<typename... Args> \
1634  inline auto Method(Args &&...args)->typename std::remove_reference<decltype(std::declval<Class>().Method(std::forward<Args>(args)...))>::type { \
1635  return this->template as<Class>().Method(std::forward<Args>(args)...); \
1636  }
1637 
1638 #define HALIDE_FORWARD_METHOD_CONST(Class, Method) \
1639  template<typename... Args> \
1640  inline auto Method(Args &&...args) const-> \
1641  typename std::remove_reference<decltype(std::declval<Class>().Method(std::forward<Args>(args)...))>::type { \
1642  this->check_gio_access(); \
1643  return this->template as<Class>().Method(std::forward<Args>(args)...); \
1644  }

2381  HALIDE_NO_USER_CODE_INLINE void assign_from_func(const Func &f) {
2382  this->check_value_writable();
2383 
2384  internal_assert(f.defined());
2385 
2386  if (this->types_defined()) {
2387  const auto &my_types = this->types();
2388  user_assert(my_types.size() == f.output_types().size())
2389  << "Cannot assign Func \"" << f.name()
2390  << "\" to Output \"" << this->name() << "\"\n"
2391  << "Output " << this->name()
2392  << " is declared to have " << my_types.size() << " tuple elements"
2393  << " but Func " << f.name()
2394  << " has " << f.output_types().size() << " tuple elements.\n";
2395  for (size_t i = 0; i < my_types.size(); i++) {
2396  user_assert(my_types[i] == f.output_types().at(i))
2397  << "Cannot assign Func \"" << f.name()
2398  << "\" to Output \"" << this->name() << "\"\n"
2399  << (my_types.size() > 1 ? "In tuple element " + std::to_string(i) + ", " : "")
2400  << "Output " << this->name()
2401  << " has declared type " << my_types[i]
2402  << " but Func " << f.name()
2403  << " has type " << f.output_types().at(i) << "\n";
2404  }
2405  }
2406  if (this->dims_defined()) {
2407  user_assert(f.dimensions() == this->dims())
2408  << "Cannot assign Func \"" << f.name()
2409  << "\" to Output \"" << this->name() << "\"\n"
2410  << "Output " << this->name()
2411  << " has declared dimensionality " << this->dims()
2412  << " but Func " << f.name()
2413  << " has dimensionality " << f.dimensions() << "\n";
2414  }
2415 
2416  internal_assert(this->exprs_.empty() && this->funcs_.size() == 1);
2417  user_assert(!this->funcs_.at(0).defined());
2418  this->funcs_[0] = f;
2419  }

2421 protected:

2430  }

2798 /** GeneratorContext is a base class that is used when using Generators (or Stubs) directly;
2799  * it is used to allow the outer context (typically, either a Generator or "top-level" code)
2800  * to specify certain information to the inner context to ensure that inner and outer
2801  * Generators are compiled in a compatible way.
2802  *
2803  * If you are using this at "top level" (e.g. with the JIT), you can construct a GeneratorContext
2804  * with a Target:
2805  * \code
2806  * auto my_stub = MyStub(
2807  * GeneratorContext(get_target_from_environment()),
2808  * // inputs
2809  * { ... },
2810  * // generator params
2811  * { ... }
2812  * );
2813  * \endcode
2814  *
2815  * Note that all Generators inherit from GeneratorContext, so if you are using a Stub
2816  * from within a Generator, you can just pass 'this' for the GeneratorContext:
2817  * \code
2818  * struct SomeGen : Generator<SomeGen> {
2819  * void generate() {
2820  * ...
2821  * auto my_stub = MyStub(
2822  * this, // GeneratorContext
2823  * // inputs
2824  * { ... },
2825  * // generator params
2826  * { ... }
2827  * );
2828  * ...
2829  * }
2830  * };
2831  * \endcode
2832  */
2833 class GeneratorContext {
2834 public:
2835  using ExternsMap = std::map<std::string, ExternalCode>;
2836 
2837  explicit GeneratorContext(const Target &t,
2838  bool auto_schedule = false,
2839  const MachineParams &machine_params = MachineParams::generic());
2840  virtual ~GeneratorContext() = default;
2841 
2842  inline Target get_target() const {
2843  return target;
2844  }
2845  inline bool get_auto_schedule() const {
2846  return auto_schedule;
2847  }
2848  inline MachineParams get_machine_params() const {
2849  return machine_params;
2850  }
2851 
2852  /** Generators can register ExternalCode objects onto
2853  * themselves. The Generator infrastructure will arrange to have
2854  * this ExternalCode appended to the Module that is finally
2855  * compiled using the Generator. This allows encapsulating
2856  * functionality that depends on external libraries or handwritten
2857  * code for various targets. The name argument should match the
2858  * name of the ExternalCode block and is used to ensure the same
2859  * code block is not duplicated in the output. Halide does not do
2860  * anything other than to compare names for equality. To guarantee
2861  * uniqueness in public code, we suggest using a Java style
2862  * inverted domain name followed by organization specific
2863  * naming. E.g.:
2864  * com.yoyodyne.overthruster.0719acd19b66df2a9d8d628a8fefba911a0ab2b7
2865  *
2866  * See test/generator/external_code_generator.cpp for example use. */
2867  inline std::shared_ptr<ExternsMap> get_externs_map() const {
2868  return externs_map;
2869  }
2870 
2871  template<typename T>
2872  inline std::unique_ptr<T> create() const {
2873  return T::create(*this);
2874  }
2875 
2876  template<typename T, typename... Args>
2877  inline std::unique_ptr<T> apply(const Args &...args) const {
2878  auto t = this->create<T>();
2879  t->apply(args...);
2880  return t;
2881  }
2882 
2883 protected:
2884  GeneratorParam<Target> target;
2885  GeneratorParam<bool> auto_schedule;
2886  GeneratorParam<MachineParams> machine_params;
2887  std::shared_ptr<ExternsMap> externs_map;
2888  std::shared_ptr<Internal::ValueTracker> value_tracker;
2889 
2890  GeneratorContext()
2891  : GeneratorContext(Target()) {
2892  }
2893 
2894  virtual void init_from_context(const Halide::GeneratorContext &context);
2895

2897  return value_tracker;
2898  }

3057  /**
3058  * Build a module that is suitable for using for gradient descent calculation in TensorFlow or PyTorch.
3059  *
3060  * Essentially:
3061  * - A new Pipeline is synthesized from the current Generator (according to the rules below)
3062  * - The new Pipeline is autoscheduled (if autoscheduling is requested, but it would be odd not to do so)
3063  * - The Pipeline is compiled to a Module and returned
3064  *
3065  * The new Pipeline is adjoint to the original; it has:
3066  * - All the same inputs as the original, in the same order
3067  * - Followed by one grad-input for each original output
3068  * - Followed by one output for each unique pairing of original-output + original-input.
3069  * (For the common case of just one original-output, this amounts to being one output for each original-input.)
3070  */

3076  * is often a bit unintuitive at present. The arguments are passed in Input<>-declaration-order,
3077  * and the types must be compatible. Array inputs are passed as std::vector<> of the relevant type.
3078  *

3215  // A Generator's creation and usage must go in a certain phase to ensure correctness;
3216  // the state machine here is advanced and checked at various points to ensure

3228  // in AOT mode, this can be skipped, going Created->GenerateCalled directly.)
3229  InputsSet,
3230 
3231  // Generator has had its generate() method called. (For Generators with
3232  // a build() method instead of generate(), this phase will be skipped
3233  // and will advance directly to ScheduleCalled.)
3234  GenerateCalled,
3235 
3236  // Generator has had its schedule() method (if any) called.
3237  ScheduleCalled,

3295  // Allow Buffer<> if:
3296  // -- we are assigning it to an Input<Buffer<>> (with compatible type and dimensions),
3297  // causing the Input<Buffer<>> to become a precompiled buffer in the generated code.
3298  // -- we are assigningit to an Input<Func>, in which case we just Func-wrap the Buffer<>.
3299  template<typename T>
3300  std::vector<StubInput> build_input(size_t i, const Buffer<T> &arg) {
3301  auto *in = param_info().inputs().at(i);
3302  check_input_is_singular(in);
3303  const auto k = in->kind();
3304  if (k == Internal::IOKind::Buffer) {
3305  Halide::Buffer<> b = arg;
3306  StubInputBuffer<> sib(b);
3307  StubInput si(sib);
3308  return {si};
3309  } else if (k == Internal::IOKind::Function) {
3310  Halide::Func f(arg.name() + "_im");
3311  f(Halide::_) = arg(Halide::_);
3312  StubInput si(f);
3313  return {si};
3314  } else {
3315  check_input_kind(in, Internal::IOKind::Buffer); // just to trigger assertion
3316  return {};
3317  }
3318  }
3319

3321  // -- we are assigning it to another Input<Buffer<>> (with compatible type and dimensions),
3322  // allowing us to simply pipe a parameter from an enclosing Generator to the Invoker.

3532  // Implementations for build_pipeline_impl(), specialized on whether we
3533  // have build() or generate()/schedule() methods.
3534 
3535  // MSVC apparently has some weirdness with the usual sfinae tricks
3536  // for detecting method-shaped things, so we can't actually use
3537  // the helpers above outside of static_assert. Instead we make as
3538  // many overloads as we can exist, and then use C++'s preference
3539  // for treating a 0 as an int rather than a double to choose one
3540  // of them.
3541  Pipeline build_pipeline_impl(double) {
3542  static_assert(!has_configure_method<T2>::value, "The configure() method is ignored if you define a build() method; use generate() instead.");
3543  static_assert(!has_schedule_method<T2>::value, "The schedule() method is ignored if you define a build() method; use generate() instead.");
3544  pre_build();
3545  Pipeline p = ((T *)this)->build();
3546  post_build();
3547  return p;
3548  }
3549 
3550  template<typename T2 = T,
3551  typename = decltype(std::declval<T2>().generate())>
3552  Pipeline build_pipeline_impl(int) {
3553  // No: configure() must be called prior to this
3554  // (and in fact, prior to calling set_inputs).
3555  //
3556  // ((T *)this)->call_configure_impl(0, 0);
3557 
3558  ((T *)this)->call_generate_impl(0);
3559  ((T *)this)->call_schedule_impl(0, 0);
3560  return get_pipeline();
3561  }

3785 // HALIDE_REGISTER_GENERATOR_ALIAS() can be used to create an an alias-with-a-particular-set-of-param-values
3786 // for a given Generator in the build system. Normally, you wouldn't want to do this;
3787 // however, some existing Halide clients have build systems that make it challenging to
3788 // specify GeneratorParams inside the build system, and this allows a somewhat simpler
3789 // customization route for them. It's highly recommended you don't use this for new code.
3790 //
3791 // The final argument is really an initializer-list of GeneratorParams, in the form
3792 // of an initializer-list for map<string, string>:
3793 //
3794 // { { "gp-name", "gp-value"} [, { "gp2-name", "gp2-value" }] }

3796 // It is specified as a variadic template argument to allow for the fact that the embedded commas
3797 // would otherwise confuse the preprocessor; since (in this case) all we're going to do is
3798 // pass it thru as-is, this is fine (and even MSVC's 'broken' __VA_ARGS__ should be OK here).

3804  } \

3808  auto g = ORIGINAL_REGISTRY_NAME##_ns::factory(context); \
